Geographic Area Prediction¶

Research Question¶

Can the geographic location be accurately predicted based on variables such as population density, net gain or loss of migrants, fertility rate, etc?

We are using this research question because the data we will be analyzing contains the populations of every country, along with other variables that could be used for predictions, such as population density and fertility rate. We will be analyzing these variables, along with others in the dataset, to try and accurately predict location based on only the other variables.

The context of this questions is predicting where(location) based on what(other factors, such as fertility rate, migrant movement).

Hypothesis:

Null hypothesis- The geographic location can be predicted based on these variables.

Alternate Hypothesis- The geographic location can not be predicted based on these variables.

I strongly believe that we will be able to accurately predict locations based on other variables. Some variables may have a stronger correlation with others, but this is what we will be finding in the analysis.

Data Collection¶

The data gathered for this analysis is public use datasets from Kaggle. No challenges in collecting data, as all data sets used are public access. A problem with using data sets like this, is you have to work around the data provided. If you create your own dataset, you can gather exactly the data needed. A problem is finding datasets that correlate with eachother, so it takes lots of time searching for correct data sets that can be used in conjunction with eachother for an analysis. I finally came across datasets that can be linked by country and state, and therefore can all be used together.

Links:

https://www.kaggle.com/peretzcohen/2019-census-us-population-data-by-state

https://www.kaggle.com/tanuprabhu/population-by-country-2020

https://www.kaggle.com/paultimothymooney/latitude-and-longitude-for-every-country-and-state

Data Explanation¶

https://www.kaggle.com/peretzcohen/2019-census-us-population-data-by-state

STATE: State in the US

POPESTIMATE2019: Population of State

lat: Lat Coordinate of Capital

long: Long Coordinate of Capital

https://www.kaggle.com/tanuprabhu/population-by-country-2020

Country: Country Name

Population (2020): Population Number

Yearly Change: Population yearly change

Net Change: Net change in population

Density (P/Km²): Population density

Land Area (Km²): Land area in square kilometers

Migrants (net): Net change in migrant population

Fert. Rate: Fertility Rate

Med. Age: Median Age

Urban Pop %: Percentage of population in urban areas

https://www.kaggle.com/paultimothymooney/latitude-and-longitude-for-every-country-and-state

country_code: Abbreviated country name

latitude: latitude of country

longitude: longitude of country

country: Full country name

usa_state_code: Abbreviated US states

usa_state_latitude: Latitude of US State

usa_state_longitude: Longitude of US State

usa_state: Full state name

Data Extraction and Preparation¶

The tools imported below are the tools used for data extraction and preparation. Numpy is used for addition data science functionality. Pandas is used to create and manipulate dataframes. These tools have the benefit of being simple to use and providing a lot of extra usage and functionality. A disadvantage is using pandas dataframe, because once the data is converted into a dataframe, we have to use only tools that cooperate with the pandas dataframe object type.

# Drawing map function
def draw_map(m, scale=0.2):
    # draw a shaded-relief image
    m.shadedrelief(scale=scale)
    
    # lats and longs are returned as a dictionary
    lats = m.drawparallels(np.linspace(-90, 90, 13))
    lons = m.drawmeridians(np.linspace(-180, 180, 13))

    # keys contain the plt.Line2D instances
    lat_lines = chain(*(tup[1][0] for tup in lats.items()))
    lon_lines = chain(*(tup[1][0] for tup in lons.items()))
    all_lines = chain(lat_lines, lon_lines)
    
    # cycle through these lines and set the desired style
    for line in all_lines:
        line.set(linestyle='-', alpha=0.3, color='w')

Interactive map¶

In [46]:
world_map= folium.Map(tiles="cartodbpositron")

marker_cluster = MarkerCluster().add_to(world_map)

#for each coordinate, create circlemarker
for i in range(len(finaldf)):
        lat = finaldf.iloc[i]['latitude']
        long = finaldf.iloc[i]['longitude']
        radius=5
        popup_text = """
        Country/State : {}<br>
        Population : {}<br>
        Yearly Change : {}<br>
        Net Change : {}<br>
        Density (P/Km²) : {}<br>
        Land Area (Km²) : {}<br>
        Migrants (net) : {}<br>
        Fert. Rate : {}<br>
        Med. Age : {}<br>
        Urban Pop % : {}<br>
        World Share : {}<br>
        """
        popup_text = popup_text.format(
            finaldf.iloc[i]['Country'],
            finaldf.iloc[i]['Population'],
            finaldf.iloc[i]['Yearly Change'],
            finaldf.iloc[i]['Net Change'],
            finaldf.iloc[i]['Density (P/Km²)'],
            finaldf.iloc[i]['Land Area (Km²)'],
            finaldf.iloc[i]['Migrants (net)'],
            finaldf.iloc[i]['Fert. Rate'],
            finaldf.iloc[i]['Med. Age'],
            finaldf.iloc[i]['Urban Pop %'],
            finaldf.iloc[i]['World Share']
                                   )
        folium.CircleMarker(location = [lat, long], radius=radius, popup= popup_text, fill =True).add_to(marker_cluster)

In [53]:
from sklearn import metrics

def print_evaluate(true, predicted):  
    mae = metrics.mean_absolute_error(true, predicted)
    mse = metrics.mean_squared_error(true, predicted)
    rmse = np.sqrt(metrics.mean_squared_error(true, predicted))
    r2_square = metrics.r2_score(true, predicted)
    print('MAE:', mae)
    print('MSE:', mse)
    print('RMSE:', rmse)
    print('R Sqaured', r2_square)
    
def evaluate(true, predicted):
    mae = metrics.mean_absolute_error(true, predicted)
    mse = metrics.mean_squared_error(true, predicted)
    rmse = np.sqrt(metrics.mean_squared_error(true, predicted))
    r2_square = metrics.r2_score(true, predicted)
    return mae, mse, rmse, r2_square

RANSAC¶

RANSAC (Random Sample consesus) data consists of "inliers", i.e., data whose distribution can be explained by some set of model parameters, though may be subject to noise, and "outliers" which are data that do not fit the model.

Elastic Net Regression¶

A linear regression model trained with L1 and L2 prior as regularizer.

This combination allows for learning a sparse model where few of the weights are non-zero like Lasso, while still maintaining the regularization properties of Ridge.

Elastic-net is useful when there are multiple features which are correlated with one another. Lasso is likely to pick one of these at random, while elastic-net is likely to pick both.

In [66]:

from tensorflow.keras.models import Sequential
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Input, Dense, Activation, Dropout
from tensorflow.keras.optimizers import Adam

X_test = np.array(X_test)
y_train = np.array(y_train)
y_test = np.array(y_test)

model = Sequential()

model.add(Dense(X_train.shape[1], activation='relu'))
model.add(Dense(32, activation='relu'))
# model.add(Dropout(0.2))

model.add(Dropout(0.1))
model.add(Dense(1))

              validation_data=(X_test,y_test),
              batch_size=1,

Data Summary and Implications¶

Can the geographic location be accurately predicted based on variables such as population density, net gain or loss of migrants, fertility rate, etc? The alternate hypothesis is correct in that the geographic location CANNOT be accurately predicted based on these variables.

We ran 10 different regression variations and the accuracy is quite low on all of them. The RMSE shows the best functions are Linear, Ridge, Elastic, Lasso, SGD, AI, and Random Forest. However, even on all of these, the R Squared scores are negative, meaning the outcome results are not reliable.

One limitation of this analysis is the data has many 0 values. There were many null values and NaN values. All of these values may have had a significant affect on the accuracy of the analysis. If there was more data filled about each and every country, the analysis may have been able to predict with much higher accuracy. However, the abundance of 0 values really made the accuracy very low and unreliable in being able to predict location. In redoing this analysis, much more complete data would need to be put together on every country involved in the study in order to run another analysis.

A course of action based on these results would be to find more sources of data to add to the data collected for this analysis. The more data that is added, the more accurate the total results will be. Finding data to fill in the blanks in this dataset would help significantly in increasing accuracy.

One direction for future study of this dataset could be finding the fertility rate of certain countries and tracking the changing fertility rates of those countries over time. Another avenue for study could be tracking the population over time, and tracking the population densities, and the urban population percentages, and seeing how the population moves around between urban and rural areas.
